SIMPLE: undermeal
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Undermeal
<hw>Un"der*meal`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>under</ets> under + <ets>m<?/l</ets> part or portion; cf. AS.
<ets>underm<?/l</ets> midday. See <er>Under</er>, <er>Meal</er> a part,
and cf. <er>Undern</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The inferior, or after,
part of the day; the afternoon.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>undermeals</qex> and in mornings.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, something occurring or done in the afternoon;
esp., an afternoon meal; supper; also, an afternoon nap; a siesta.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Another great supper, or <qex>undermeal</qex>, was made ready for
them, coming home from ditching and plowing.</q> <rj><qau>Withals
(1608).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I think I am furnished with Cattern [Catharine] pears for one
<qex>undermeal</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a narrower limit than the forty years' <qex>undermeal</qex> of
the seven sleepers.</q> <rj><qau>Nash.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Undermine</ent>⟦br⟧
